European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Maybe it has to do with the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Maybe it's about the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that for centuries has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe.
Might all these factors, combined, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political entity whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
Das ist so, als ob ein Teil eines Zimmers geheizt werden könnte, während es im anderen Teil kalt bliebe.
Es gibt nur ein Europa, trotz seiner Verschiedenheit.
Jedes bedeutende Ereignis ruft quer durch Europa ein Echo hervor.
Wenn Europa eins werden soll, wenn die Europäische Union die neuen postkommunistischen Demokratien aufnehmen soll  was im Interesse Europas liegt , müssen eine Reihe essentieller Aufgaben angegangen werden, innerhalb der neuen Demokratien wie auch in der Europäischen sowie der atlantischen Gemeinschaft.
Zunächst muss Europa die Gemeinschaftlichkeit in den postkommunistischen Ländern fördern, indem sie die Zivilgesellschaft wiederherstellt.
Denn eine lebendige Gesellschaft kann nicht von oben wiederaufgebaut werden.
Europa muss seinen neuen Demokratien also helfen, organischer Teil eines gemeinsamen kontinentalen Bekenntnisses zur Vertiefung und Stärkung der Zivilgesellschaft zu werden.
Je vielfältiger europäische zivilgesellschaftliche Strukturen werden und je mehr sie miteinander verbunden sind, um so besser werden die neuen Demokratien für die Mitgliedschaft in der EU ausgerüstet und um so stabiler werden sie als Staaten sein.
Um dies zu erreichen, muss Europa die neuen Demokratien dazu ermutigen, diverse Solidaraufgaben selbstverwalteten Institutionen und gemeinnützigen oder öffentlichen Dienstleistungsorganisationen zu übertragen.
Je tiefer die Ebene der Umverteilung ist, um so transparenter und ökonomischer wird es sein; und um so besser wird es jene sozialen Bedürfnisse befriedigen, die die zentralen Behörden nicht erkennen können.
<span class="start_mark"><span class="line_number">#1 </span><span class="translation"><span class="original">Die soziale Solidarität wird authentischer werden, wenn sie eng mit den Menschen oder ihren Vereinigungen verbunden ist.</span></span></span>
<span class="start_mark"><span class="line_number">#2 </span><span class="translation"><span class="original">Eine authentische Solidarität unter Menschen, sozialen Gruppen, Siedlungen und Regionen ist auch die sicherste Grundlage für jene Formen von Solidarität, die nur Staaten ausüben können.</span></span></span>
<span class="start_mark"><span class="line_number">#3 </span><span class="translation"><span class="original">Ein bitteres Kapitel in der modernen europäischen Geschichte war die Beschwichtigungspolitik mit ihrem Verzicht auf europäische Solidarität, was zur Kapitulation von München führte.</span></span></span>
<span class="start_mark"><span class="line_number">#4 </span><span class="translation"><span class="original">Diese Erfahrung ist immer noch ein energischer Aufruf zu Wachsamkeit.</span></span></span>
<span class="start_mark"><span class="line_number">#5 </span><span class="translation"><span class="original">Dem Übel muss man entgegentreten, sobald es erscheint, es reicht aber nicht, wenn lediglich Regierungen handeln.</span></span></span>
Denn government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern about security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should distinguish itself through the ability to make rapid decisions and to implement collective decisions quickly into action  reforms that the recent developments in Yugoslavia have shown to be necessary.
The intervention of NATO last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of pan-European security requires interventions beyond the EU borders.
Je stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate does not come about, even though an intervention would be in the interest of many people, indeed of all of Europe, and even of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was unprepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
But further measures in the field of preventive security are needed, but it is also necessary that this security reflects the values of the expanded civil society in Europe.
Tens of thousands of lives and enormous amounts of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, only timid actions were taken.
These failures resulted from various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still have been passive spectators to the horrors in Kosovo.
Europe cannot be dependent on the USA forever, especially not regarding European problems.
It must be capable of finding independent solutions.
It is inconceivable that the EU can remain a respected part of the world order if it fails to develop means and ways to protect human rights not only on its own territory but also in regions that may join it one day.
Such an EU expansion is only feasible if it goes hand in hand with a bold reform of the EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the intergovernmental conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for advancing the union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that will perhaps take decades and should be guided by a lasting commitment to speeding up and making more transparent EU decision-making.
An issue related to institutional reform is how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be overridden by the larger ones, while still taking the size of individual states into due consideration.
A possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would be elected not directly, but from their own ranks by the parliaments of the member states.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e., the current Parliament – would thus reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber, with the same number of representatives for each state, would increase equality.
At some point, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, comprehensible constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
A such a constitution would require two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and the states concerned, as well as the underlying values and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships to each other.
Such a charter would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal overstate feared by euroskeptics.
It would, however, help citizens in a integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to understand it better, to see the importance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
